{"id":"2205.06244","submitter":"Arkya Chatterjee","authors":"Arkya Chatterjee, Xiao-Gang Wen","title":"Holographic theory for the emergence and the symmetry protection of\n  gaplessness and for continuous phase transitions","comments":"44 pages, 22 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el hep-th math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A gapless state may be fully characterized by its emergent symmetries. Finite\nemergent symmetries can be described by a topological order $M$ in one higher\ndimension (i.e. by a categorical symmetry). The patterns of spontaneous\ncategorical symmetry breaking are classified by condensable algebras $A$ formed\nby excitations in $M$. Various categorical symmetry breaking patterns can\ndescribe spontaneous symmetry breaking (SSB) orders, symmetry protected\ntopological orders, symmetry enriched topological orders, gapless critical\npoints, etc., in a unified way. The local low energy properties of a state with\nspontaneous categorical symmetry breaking pattern $A$ are exactly reproduced by\na 1-condensed boundary state of $M_{/A}$, where $M_{/A}$ is the topological\norder obtained from $M$ by condensing $A$. The properties (such as scaling\ndimensions) of a gapless state can be calculated from its corresponding\nunbroken categorical symmetry $M_{/A}$ via an algebraic number theoretical\nmethod. For example, a state with symmetry breaking pattern $A$ can be gapped\nif $M_{/A}$ is trivial and must be gapless if $M_{/A}$ is non-trivial. The\nrelations between the condensable algebras also help us determine the structure\nof the global phase diagram. For 1+1D $Z_2 \\times Z_2'$ symmetry with mixed\nanomaly, there is a stable continuous transition between the $Z_2$-SSB phase\nand the $Z_2$-SSB phase. The critical point is the same as the $Z_4$ symmetry\nbreaking critical point. With $S_3$ symmetry, there are four gapped phases with\nunbroken symmetries $S_3, Z_3, Z_2$, and $Z_1$. We find a duality between two\ntransitions $S_3$ to $ Z_1$ and $Z_3$ to $Z_2$. The gapped and gapless states\nfor 1+1D bosonic systems with anomalous $S_3$ symmetries are obtained as well.\nFor example, anomalous $S_3^{(2)}$ symmetry can have a stable chiral gapless\nphase described by $E(8)_1 \\times \\overline{so}(9)_2$ CFT.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 12 May 2022 17:43:58 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 16 May 2022 22:03:50 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 27 Dec 2022 01:47:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-29"}
